snippet.textDisplay:
Interference is of fairly low relevance to HDMI, it's inherently resilient being a differential link, and foreseen shielding takes great care of that.

What it does offer is galvanic decoupling. This way device grounds are not connected with each other and you can avoid ground loops. Musicians might appreciate this cable for this reason, as it can leave their laptop floating when connecting to an external display. They also have enough heavy cables already and might like the weight saving when travelling. And they absolutely love their cables looking all kinds of crazy so they easily know what cable goes where. Granted this would be an extremely uncommon use case, as travelling musicians tend to avoid external displays.

snippet.textDisplay: Now this is just stupid...  I've used optic cables for years; from military to Toslink audio to Celerity HDMI.  On these, the USB power is used to power the light-to-digital conversion circuits in each end.  And if you play "rodeo lasso" or "fasion headband" with an optic cable, you run the risk of snapping the fiber inside... trust me.  Done it, had to replace it.  There is a bend-radius limitation on all fiber cables.  They're really sturdy and reliable, but it's not as flexible as copper.  And as far as distance signal loss, nothing matches optic cabels for lack of signal degradation over distance.  Copper (and any wiring) looses signal strength over distance... if you're talking 15 feet or more.  The longer the copper cable, the more signal loss.  RG6 and CAT 6 cables overcome this by the type of copper used, the way it's constructed and the strength and type of signal output.  HDMI is a very low voltage system,  which is why it's hard to find a 50 foot UHD HDMI cable.  The minimum distance I put fiber in the system is 20 feet... otherwise it's copper.  AND DO WE REALLY NEED AN RGB FLASHY CABLE?  This is another shiny object.  Or like my dog... SQUIRREL!!!
